{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1a1f7c4c-92ea-400f-9a23-80bdda7b0cdb","content":"Here are the four breaking changes in .NET 10:\n\n**1. `System.Text.Json` — duplicate property names now throw**\nThe discriminator `\"Type\"` collides with the `Type` property. .NET 10 throws `InvalidOperationException` instead of emitting invalid JSON. **Fix:** rename the discriminator or the property, or add `[JsonIgnore]` to `Type`.\n\n**2. `XmlSerializer` — `[Obsolete]` properties now serialized**\n.NET 10 includes `[Obsolete]` members in XML output. Your `Address` field will now appear alongside `ShippingAddress`. **Fix:** add `[XmlIgnore]` to `Address` if you want it excluded.\n\n**3. `MailAddress` — stricter RFC compliance**\n`user..name@example.com` has consecutive dots, which violates RFC 5321. .NET 10 rejects this with `FormatException`. **Fix:** validate/normalize addresses before constructing `MailAddress`, or catch the exception.\n\n**4. `Uri` — maximum length enforced**\n.NET 10 enforces a max URI length (~65K chars). URIs exceeding this throw `UriFormatException`. If your 10K URLs are under that limit they're fine, but test your longest cases.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ebeede4-c22f-4a9b-9987-6d7b19da61a5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about breaking changes when migrating from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each scenario they've described based on my knowledge of .NET 10 breaking changes.\n\nLet me think through each case:\n\n1. **JsonPolymorphic with duplicate property names**: In .NET 9, `System.Text.Json` allowed serializing objects that would produce duplicate JSON property names (the type discriminator and the actual property having the same name). In .NET 10, this throws an `InvalidOperationException` because duplicate property names produce invalid JSON. This is a known breaking change.\n\n2. **XmlSerializer with `[Obsolete]` properties**: In .NET 10, there's a breaking change where `XmlSerializer` now seri